law.text:
// EFFECTIVE UNTIL MAY 31, 2013 PER CHAPTERS 626 AND 627 OF 2008 //
A person shall be certified by the Commissioner before operating a public-private health care program in the State.
An applicant for certification shall:
be a nonprofit corporation that, in accordance with its charter, is organized for the purpose of establishing and operating a public-private health care program; and
file with the Commissioner:
an application on the form that the Commissioner requires containing the information that the Commissioner considers necessary;
copies of the following documents, certified by at least two of the executive officers of the applicant:
articles of incorporation of the applicant that include the applicant's corporate mission statement, and all amendments to the articles;
bylaws of the applicant, and all amendments to the bylaws;
a list of the name, address, and biographical information for each member of the board of directors of the applicant; and
a list of the beginning and ending terms of office of each member of the board of directors of the applicant;
the written agreement with each county in which the applicant proposes to operate a public-private health care program that specifies the obligations of each party to the agreement;
a description of the public-private health care program the applicant proposes to operate, including:
the criteria used to determine who is a qualifying individual;
the arrangements for the delivery of health care services;
the payment obligations of participants;
the internal complaint process available to participants; and
the procedures to be used to monitor applications for enrollment to determine whether an individual has voluntarily terminated coverage under a health benefit plan issued under Title 15, Subtitle 12 of this article;
all forms, agreements, advertising, or other documents that will be provided to participants; and
any other information or documents that the Commissioner considers necessary to ensure compliance with this subtitle.
